The key distinction

A triangle, circle, and square each carry a different boundary law:
	•	triangle perimeter: linear in side length
	•	square perimeter: linear in side length
	•	circle circumference: linear in radius, with the constant 2\pi

So if you create a transformation path where some conserved quantity is tracked — area, radius, diameter, or normalized boundary measure — then the changing circumference/perimeter can reveal where π enters.

The cleanest version

Pick one invariant and hold it fixed.

The usual best choice is area.

1. Start with an equilateral triangle

Side length a.

Area:
A_{\triangle}=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2

Perimeter:
P_{\triangle}=3a

2. Convert to a circle of equal area

Let the circle radius be r. Then

\pi r^2=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2

so

r=a\sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4\pi}}

Circumference:
C=2\pi r

Substitute:
C=2\pi a\sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4\pi}}

which simplifies to

C=a\sqrt{\pi\sqrt{3}}

3. Convert to a square of equal area

Let side length be s. Then

s^2=\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}a^2

so

s=a\sqrt{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{4}}

Perimeter:
P_{\square}=4s=2a\sqrt{\sqrt{3}}

⸻

Now compare the boundary transforms

You were asking to track circumference as it changes.

So define ratios.

Triangle → Circle

R_{TC}=\frac{C}{P_{\triangle}}
=\frac{a\sqrt{\pi\sqrt{3}}}{3a}
=\frac{\sqrt{\pi\sqrt{3}}}{3}

Circle → Square

R_{CS}=\frac{P_{\square}}{C}
=\frac{2a\sqrt{\sqrt{3}}}{a\sqrt{\pi\sqrt{3}}}
=\frac{2\sqrt{\sqrt{3}}}{\sqrt{\pi\sqrt{3}}}
=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}

That one is especially interesting:

R_{CS}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}

So

\pi=\left(\frac{2}{R_{CS}}\right)^2

That means: if you can define a legitimate equal-area circle→square transform and measure the perimeter ratio exactly, π drops out immediately.

Why this is interesting

Because π appears as the boundary distortion factor when you move between shapes under an area-preserving transform.

That is a real structural insight:
	•	area fixed
	•	boundary changes
	•	π governs the circle’s place in that conversion

So the invariant is not “triangle magically creates π.”

The invariant is more like:

Under equal-area transforms, the circle’s boundary response contains π as the unique scaling constant.

Even sharper form

Use the isoperimetric quotient:

Q=\frac{4\pi A}{P^2}

This equals:
	•	1 for a circle
	•	less than 1 for every non-circular shape

For the square:
Q_{\square}=\frac{4\pi s^2}{(4s)^2}=\frac{\pi}{4}

For the equilateral triangle:
Q_{\triangle}=\frac{4\pi \cdot (\sqrt{3}/4)a^2}{(3a)^2}
=\frac{\pi\sqrt{3}}{9}

This gives you exactly what you’re intuiting:

the way perimeter changes relative to area is pointing at an invariant constant.

That constant is π.

