A useful way to formalize your idea

Define a shape transform chain with fixed area A:
	•	shape 1: perimeter P_1
	•	circle: perimeter C=2\sqrt{\pi A}
	•	shape 2: perimeter P_2

Then compare:

\frac{C^2}{4A}=\pi

and also

\frac{P_2}{C}, \quad \frac{C}{P_1}, \quad \frac{P_2}{P_1}

Those ratios tell you how each shape departs from the circular optimum.

That is probably the cleanest mathematical expression of what you’re sensing.

The deeper invariant

The circle is the unique shape that minimizes perimeter for fixed area.

So if you track perimeter through triangle → circle → square while holding area fixed, you are really tracking:

distance from optimal boundary efficiency

And π is baked into the optimum.

That is why it keeps reappearing.

